CODE 3.1.1

m0 <- rnorm(1000,0,1)
m10 <- numeric()
m100 <- numeric()
m1000 <- numeric()
for (i in 1:1000){
  m10[i] <- mean(rnorm(10,0,1))
  m100[i] <- mean(rnorm(100,0,1))
  m1000[i] <- mean(rnorm(1000,0,1))
}
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
hist(m0)
hist(m10)
hist(m100)
hist(m1000)

CODE 3.1.2

qqnorm(m0)

ANSWER 3.1.2

The distribution looks normal.

CODE 3.1.3

m <- data.frame(m0,m10,m100,m1000)
# mean
mmean <- apply(m, 2, mean)
mmean
##            m0           m10          m100         m1000 
## -0.0613951233  0.0148647672  0.0014310703  0.0008853047
# var
mvar <- apply(m, 2, var)
mvar
##           m0          m10         m100        m1000 
## 1.0339190735 0.0937216116 0.0099040850 0.0009947532
# var ratio
mvar[1]/mvar[2:4]
##        m10       m100      m1000 
##   11.03181  104.39319 1039.37245

ANSWER 3.1.3

The means are not substantially different from each other. The variances are different from each other. The ratio between Var(m0) and Var(m10),Var(m100),Var(m1000) are about 10,100,1000. A general formula to derive the Variance of any distribution of the means Xn for any given n would be \(\frac{\sigma}{n}\)

CODE 3.2.1

r0 <- rexp(1000,1)
r10 <- numeric()
r100 <- numeric()
r1000 <- numeric()
for (i in 1:1000){
  r10[i] <- mean(rexp(10,1))
  r100[i] <- mean(rexp(100,1))
  r1000[i] <- mean(rexp(1000,1))
}
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
hist(r0)
hist(r10)
hist(r100)
hist(r1000)

CODE 3.2.2

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
qqnorm(r0)
qqnorm(r10)
qqnorm(r100)
qqnorm(r1000)

ANSWER 3.2.2

The exponential values are not normally distributed. The means are normally distributed.

CODE 3.2.3

r <- data.frame(r0,r10,r100,r1000)
# mean
rmean <- apply(r, 2, mean)
rmean
##        r0       r10      r100     r1000 
## 1.0162727 0.9949020 0.9992306 0.9997290
# var
rvar <- apply(r, 2, var)
rvar
##          r0         r10        r100       r1000 
## 0.998760565 0.098442796 0.009488062 0.001050716
# var ratio
rvar[1]/rvar[2:4]
##       r10      r100     r1000 
##  10.14559 105.26497 950.55201

ANSWER 3.2.3

The means are not substantially different from each other. The variances are different from each other. The ratio between Var(r0) and Var(r10),Var(r100),Var(r1000) are about 10,100,1000.
